{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01LJDR3VVXT6pfo7AaV3YHCH","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01KgyiVwHVhuEGou4iYQFSfj","name":"mcp__loop__get_page","input":{"workspaceId":"T0RTUHxtaWNyb3NvZnQuc2hhcmVwb2ludC1kZi5jb218YiFsUlpRZmVUWlEwQzlJb1J3RzVwcUFpQXJTV3lSOE5wQmlvcVZ6TGozTUc5Ri0zUlFmMGNyUW9rSTdmMUlwaWhTfDAxS1hKV1Q1N0VLUUxYWFdEM1NaQzJENDIyV0pDN0NNVkQ=","pageId":"bWljcm9zb2Z0LnNoYXJlcG9pbnQtZGYuY29tLGIhbFJaUWZlVFpRMEM5SW9Sd0c1cHFBaUFyU1d5UjhOcEJpb3FWekxqM01HOUYtM1JRZjBjclFva0k3ZjFJcGloUywwMUtYSldUNVo1SzNBTjM2N1NTSkZLV1RZUU9KTTNBMzdJ"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1217,"cache_read_input_tokens":54450,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1217,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4004397f-9402-4049-ba0c-52ed9b7104fc","uuid":"1c9ed4b6-f9aa-4b10-8dd3-a7ff67df89c7"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01KgyiVwHVhuEGou4iYQFSfj","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"id\": \"bWljcm9zb2Z0LnNoYXJlcG9pbnQtZGYuY29tLGIhbFJaUWZlVFpRMEM5SW9Sd0c1cHFBaUFyU1d5UjhOcEJpb3FWekxqM01HOUYtM1JRZjBjclFva0k3ZjFJcGloUywwMUtYSldUNVo1SzNBTjM2N1NTSkZLV1RZUU9KTTNBMzdJ\",\n  \"title\": \"Korean Food Culture\",\n  \"content\": \"# Korean Food Culture\\n\\n## Overview\\n\\nKorean cuisine (**hansik**, 한식) is one of the world's most vibrant and flavorful food traditions. Rooted in centuries of agricultural practice, Confucian philosophy, and seasonal eating, Korean food culture emphasizes balance, fermentation, and communal dining.\\n\\n## Core Principles\\n\\n### Bap and Banchan (밥과 반찬)\\n\\nA traditional Korean meal centers on **bap** (steamed rice) accompanied by an array of **banchan** (side dishes). A typical home meal includes 3-5 banchan, while formal occasions may feature 12 or more. This structure reflects the Korean value of variety and nutritional balance.\\n\\n### The Five Flavors and Five Colors\\n\\nKorean cooking follows the principle of **obangsaek** (오방색) — five colors (white, black, red, yellow, green) representing five elements and directions. Dishes also balance five tastes: sweet, sour, salty, bitter, and spicy.\\n\\n### Fermentation (발효)\\n\\nKorea has one of the world's richest fermentation traditions. Fermented foods are central to daily meals and include:\\n\\n- **Kimchi** (김치) — fermented vegetables, most commonly napa cabbage\\n- **Doenjang** (된장) — fermented soybean paste\\n- **Gochujang** (고추장) — fermented red chili paste\\n- **Jeotgal** (젓갈) — salted and fermented seafood\\n- **Makgeolli** (막걸리) — fermented rice wine\\n\\n## Iconic Dishes\\n\\n### Kimchi (김치)\\n\\nMore than just a side dish, kimchi is a cultural symbol. With over 200 varieties, it is made year-round but traditionally prepared in bulk during **kimjang** (김장), a communal late-autumn event recognized by UNESCO as an Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity.\\n\\n### Bibimbap (비빔밥)\\n\\nLiterally meaning \\\"mixed rice,\\\" bibimbap is a colorful bowl of rice topped with sauteed vegetables, gochujang, and often a fried egg or sliced meat. Each region has its own variation, with Jeonju bibimbap being the most famous.\\n\\n### Korean BBQ (고기구이)\\n\\nGrilling meat at the table is a beloved social dining experience. Popular cuts include **samgyeopsal** (pork belly), **galbi** (short ribs), and **bulgogi** (marinated beef). The meal is always accompanied by lettuce wraps, ssamjang dipping sauce, and banchan.\\n\\n### Jjigae and Tang (찌개와 탕)\\n\\nStews and soups are essential to Korean meals:\\n\\n- **Kimchi jjigae** — kimchi stew with pork or tuna\\n- **Doenjang jjigae** — soybean paste stew with vegetables\\n- **Sundubu jjigae** — soft tofu stew\\n- **Samgyetang** (삼계탕) — ginseng chicken soup, a summer stamina dish\\n\\n## Dining Etiquette\\n\\n- Elders eat first; younger diners wait before beginning\\n- Rice and soup bowls stay on the table (not lifted)\\n- Metal chopsticks and a long-handled spoon are used together\\n- Pouring drinks for others (especially elders) is a sign of respect\\n- Sharing dishes from common plates is the norm\\n\\n## Street Food Culture (길거리 음식)\\n\\nKorean street food is a world unto itself. Markets like **Gwangjang Market** and **Myeongdong** in Seoul offer:\\n\\n- **Tteokbokki** (떡볶이) — spicy rice cakes\\n- **Hotteok** (호떡) — sweet filled pancakes\\n- **Gimbap** (김밥) — seaweed rice rolls\\n- **Sundae** (순대) — blood sausage\\n- **Bungeoppang** (붕어빵) — fish-shaped pastry with sweet red bean filling\\n\\n## Modern Trends\\n\\nKorean food culture continues to evolve with the global **hallyu** (Korean Wave). K-food has gained worldwide popularity, with Korean fried chicken, instant ramyeon, and convenience store culture becoming global phenomena. The rise of **mukbang** (먹방) — eating broadcast videos — has further amplified Korean food's international reach.\\n\\n## Seasonal and Festive Foods\\n\\n- **Tteokguk** (떡국) — rice cake soup eaten on Lunar New Year\\n- **Songpyeon** (송편) — half-moon rice cakes for Chuseok (harvest festival)\\n- **Patbingsu** (팥빙수) — shaved ice dessert enjoyed in summer\\n- **Naengmyeon** (냉면) — cold buckwheat noodles, a summer favorite\\n\\n\"\n}"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4004397f-9402-4049-ba0c-52ed9b7104fc","uuid":"6087a1b3-85e0-44c2-a53e-040594a580fb","tool_use_result":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"id\": \"bWljcm9zb2Z0LnNoYXJlcG9pbnQtZGYuY29tLGIhbFJaUWZlVFpRMEM5SW9Sd0c1cHFBaUFyU1d5UjhOcEJpb3FWekxqM01HOUYtM1JRZjBjclFva0k3ZjFJcGloUywwMUtYSldUNVo1SzNBTjM2N1NTSkZLV1RZUU9KTTNBMzdJ\",\n  \"title\": \"Korean Food Culture\",\n  \"content\": \"# Korean Food Culture\\n\\n## Overview\\n\\nKorean cuisine (**hansik**, 한식) is one of the world's most vibrant and flavorful food traditions. Rooted in centuries of agricultural practice, Confucian philosophy, and seasonal eating, Korean food culture emphasizes balance, fermentation, and communal dining.\\n\\n## Core Principles\\n\\n### Bap and Banchan (밥과 반찬)\\n\\nA traditional Korean meal centers on **bap** (steamed rice) accompanied by an array of **banchan** (side dishes). A typical home meal includes 3-5 banchan, while formal occasions may feature 12 or more. This structure reflects the Korean value of variety and nutritional balance.\\n\\n### The Five Flavors and Five Colors\\n\\nKorean cooking follows the principle of **obangsaek** (오방색) — five colors (white, black, red, yellow, green) representing five elements and directions. Dishes also balance five tastes: sweet, sour, salty, bitter, and spicy.\\n\\n### Fermentation (발효)\\n\\nKorea has one of the world's richest fermentation traditions. Fermented foods are central to daily meals and include:\\n\\n- **Kimchi** (김치) — fermented vegetables, most commonly napa cabbage\\n- **Doenjang** (된장) — fermented soybean paste\\n- **Gochujang** (고추장) — fermented red chili paste\\n- **Jeotgal** (젓갈) — salted and fermented seafood\\n- **Makgeolli** (막걸리) — fermented rice wine\\n\\n## Iconic Dishes\\n\\n### Kimchi (김치)\\n\\nMore than just a side dish, kimchi is a cultural symbol. With over 200 varieties, it is made year-round but traditionally prepared in bulk during **kimjang** (김장), a communal late-autumn event recognized by UNESCO as an Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity.\\n\\n### Bibimbap (비빔밥)\\n\\nLiterally meaning \\\"mixed rice,\\\" bibimbap is a colorful bowl of rice topped with sauteed vegetables, gochujang, and often a fried egg or sliced meat. Each region has its own variation, with Jeonju bibimbap being the most famous.\\n\\n### Korean BBQ (고기구이)\\n\\nGrilling meat at the table is a beloved social dining experience. Popular cuts include **samgyeopsal** (pork belly), **galbi** (short ribs), and **bulgogi** (marinated beef). The meal is always accompanied by lettuce wraps, ssamjang dipping sauce, and banchan.\\n\\n### Jjigae and Tang (찌개와 탕)\\n\\nStews and soups are essential to Korean meals:\\n\\n- **Kimchi jjigae** — kimchi stew with pork or tuna\\n- **Doenjang jjigae** — soybean paste stew with vegetables\\n- **Sundubu jjigae** — soft tofu stew\\n- **Samgyetang** (삼계탕) — ginseng chicken soup, a summer stamina dish\\n\\n## Dining Etiquette\\n\\n- Elders eat first; younger diners wait before beginning\\n- Rice and soup bowls stay on the table (not lifted)\\n- Metal chopsticks and a long-handled spoon are used together\\n- Pouring drinks for others (especially elders) is a sign of respect\\n- Sharing dishes from common plates is the norm\\n\\n## Street Food Culture (길거리 음식)\\n\\nKorean street food is a world unto itself. Markets like **Gwangjang Market** and **Myeongdong** in Seoul offer:\\n\\n- **Tteokbokki** (떡볶이) — spicy rice cakes\\n- **Hotteok** (호떡) — sweet filled pancakes\\n- **Gimbap** (김밥) — seaweed rice rolls\\n- **Sundae** (순대) — blood sausage\\n- **Bungeoppang** (붕어빵) — fish-shaped pastry with sweet red bean filling\\n\\n## Modern Trends\\n\\nKorean food culture continues to evolve with the global **hallyu** (Korean Wave). K-food has gained worldwide popularity, with Korean fried chicken, instant ramyeon, and convenience store culture becoming global phenomena. The rise of **mukbang** (먹방) — eating broadcast videos — has further amplified Korean food's international reach.\\n\\n## Seasonal and Festive Foods\\n\\n- **Tteokguk** (떡국) — rice cake soup eaten on Lunar New Year\\n- **Songpyeon** (송편) — half-moon rice cakes for Chuseok (harvest festival)\\n- **Patbingsu** (팥빙수) — shaved ice dessert enjoyed in summer\\n- **Naengmyeon** (냉면) — cold buckwheat noodles, a summer favorite\\n\\n\"\n}"}]}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01EdyWK23A1opeU9i9E3eWyz","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Got it! Here's the summary of the Loop page:\n\n---\n\n## Summary: \"Korean Food Culture\"\n\n**Title:** Korean Food Culture  \n**Link:** [SharePoint Loop Page](https://microsoft.sharepoint-df.com/:fl:/g/contentstorage/x8FNO-xtskuCRX2_fMTHLRo8YaOBF1tMsxtMIJmILxo/IQA9VsDd-_KSSqtPEHJZsG_oAWNunCpWJ_UnEQ1TUyEC-u0)\n\nThis is an informational page about **Korean cuisine (hansik, 한식)**. It covers:\n\n1. **Core Principles** — Korean meals center on rice (bap) with multiple side dishes (banchan). Cooking follows the obangsaek principle of five colors/flavors for balance. Fermentation is foundational, with staples like kimchi, doenjang, gochujang, jeotgal, and makgeolli.\n\n2. **Iconic Dishes** — Kimchi (200+ varieties, UNESCO-recognized kimjang tradition), bibimbap (mixed rice bowls, Jeonju style most famous), Korean BBQ (samgyeopsal, galbi, bulgogi as social dining), and stews/soups (kimchi jjigae, doenjang jjigae, samgyetang).\n\n3. **Dining Etiquette** — Elders eat first, bowls stay on the table, metal chopsticks + long spoon used together, pouring drinks for others shows respect, communal plate sharing is the norm.\n\n4. **Street Food** — Tteokbokki, hotteok, gimbap, sundae, bungeoppang at famous markets like Gwangjang and Myeongdong.\n\n5. **Modern Trends** — K-food's global rise through hallyu (Korean Wave), popularity of Korean fried chicken, instant ramyeon, convenience store culture, and mukbang (eating broadcasts).\n\n6. **Seasonal Foods** — Tteokguk for Lunar New Year, songpyeon for Chuseok, patbingsu and naengmyeon for summer.\n\n---\n\nNow let me write my learnings file."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1982,"cache_read_input_tokens":55667,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1982,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4004397f-9402-4049-ba0c-52ed9b7104fc","uuid":"971e8527-5733-409c-8467-4222c066ab42"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01EdyWK23A1opeU9i9E3eWyz","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01SSzEvcr47v5yHsur29z8bu","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\yemishin\\.squad\\notes\\inbox\\dallas-2026-03-14.md","content":"# Dallas Learnings — 2026-03-14 (W023)\n\n## Task\nRead and summarize a Loop page from a SharePoint content storage URL.\n\n## Findings\n\n### Loop Page Access from SharePoint Content Storage URLs\n- SharePoint content storage URLs (`/contentstorage/...`) require special handling — they are NOT the user's Copilot workspace (source: URL path `/contentstorage/x8FNO-xtskuCRX2_fMTHLRo8YaOBF1tMsxtMIJmILxo`)\n- The `decode_url` MCP tool does NOT support SharePoint `:fl:` URLs — only Loop `/p/` and `/join/` URL formats (source: `mcp__loop__decode_url` error: \"Expected Loop URL path like /p/{payload}\")\n- WebFetch returns 401 for SharePoint URLs (authenticated content) (source: WebFetch 401 error)\n- Graph API returns 403 \"accessDenied\" for content storage sites (source: Graph API `/v1.0/sites/` 403 response)\n- SharePoint REST API returns 401 \"invalidScope\" — Azure CLI app lacks `user_impersonation` for SPO (source: SharePoint API 401 response)\n\n### Correct Workflow for SharePoint Loop URLs\n1. **Decode the nav parameter** — it's base64-encoded, containing URL params: `s` (site path), `d` (driveId), `f` (itemId), `x` (workspace JSON with `w` and `i` fields)\n2. **Extract workspace podId** from `x.w` (base64-encoded `ODSP|domain|driveId|itemId` string) — use this as `workspaceId` for Loop MCP\n3. **List pages** via `mcp__loop__list_pages` with the workspace podId to find the target page and get correct `odspMetadata`\n4. **Construct pageId** from listing's `odspMetadata` — NOT from the URL's nav params (driveId may differ slightly!)\n5. **Read page** via `mcp__loop__get_page` with constructed pageId\n\n### Critical Gotcha: DriveId Mismatch\n- The driveId in the URL's `d` nav param (`...MH9F...`) differed from the actual driveId in the workspace listing (`...MG9F...`) (source: nav param vs `mcp__loop__list_pages` odspMetadata comparison)\n- Always use the driveId from `list_pages` odspMetadata, NOT from the URL's nav parameter\n- This single character difference (`H` vs `G`) causes 404 \"itemNotFound\" errors\n\n### Platform Notes\n- `python3` unavailable on this Windows machine (Microsoft Store stub) — use `node -e` for all scripting (confirmed from squad notes)\n- `uuidgen` unavailable — use `require('crypto').randomUUID()` in Node.js\n\n## Conventions\n- Loop MCP `list_pages` can return very large results (280K+ chars for workspaces with many pages) — search by itemId programmatically rather than reading raw output\n- The `pageId` field in `list_pages` results can be `undefined` — construct it manually from `odspMetadata` fields: `base64(domain + \",\" + driveId + \",\" + itemId)`\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1982,"cache_read_input_tokens":55667,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1982,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4004397f-9402-4049-ba0c-52ed9b7104fc","uuid":"df328285-5231-41d2-b188-ba47b48c041f"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01SSzEvcr47v5yHsur29z8bu","type":"tool_result","content":"File created successfully at: C:\\Users\\yemishin\\.squad\\notes\\inbox\\dallas-2026-03-14.md"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4004397f-9402-4049-ba0c-52ed9b7104fc","uuid":"21bc099e-00d9-4715-940e-e8313c6a1e29","tool_use_result":{"type":"create","filePath":"C:\\Users\\yemishin\\.squad\\notes\\inbox\\dallas-2026-03-14.md","content":"# Dallas Learnings — 2026-03-14 (W023)\n\n## Task\nRead and summarize a Loop page from a SharePoint content storage URL.\n\n## Findings\n\n### Loop Page Access from SharePoint Content Storage URLs\n- SharePoint content storage URLs (`/contentstorage/...`) require special handling — they are NOT the user's Copilot workspace (source: URL path `/contentstorage/x8FNO-xtskuCRX2_fMTHLRo8YaOBF1tMsxtMIJmILxo`)\n- The `decode_url` MCP tool does NOT support SharePoint `:fl:` URLs — only Loop `/p/` and `/join/` URL formats (source: `mcp__loop__decode_url` error: \"Expected Loop URL path like /p/{payload}\")\n- WebFetch returns 401 for SharePoint URLs (authenticated content) (source: WebFetch 401 error)\n- Graph API returns 403 \"accessDenied\" for content storage sites (source: Graph API `/v1.0/sites/` 403 response)\n- SharePoint REST API returns 401 \"invalidScope\" — Azure CLI app lacks `user_impersonation` for SPO (source: SharePoint API 401 response)\n\n### Correct Workflow for SharePoint Loop URLs\n1. **Decode the nav parameter** — it's base64-encoded, containing URL params: `s` (site path), `d` (driveId), `f` (itemId), `x` (workspace JSON with `w` and `i` fields)\n2. **Extract workspace podId** from `x.w` (base64-encoded `ODSP|domain|driveId|itemId` string) — use this as `workspaceId` for Loop MCP\n3. **List pages** via `mcp__loop__list_pages` with the workspace podId to find the target page and get correct `odspMetadata`\n4. **Construct pageId** from listing's `odspMetadata` — NOT from the URL's nav params (driveId may differ slightly!)\n5. **Read page** via `mcp__loop__get_page` with constructed pageId\n\n### Critical Gotcha: DriveId Mismatch\n- The driveId in the URL's `d` nav param (`...MH9F...`) differed from the actual driveId in the workspace listing (`...MG9F...`) (source: nav param vs `mcp__loop__list_pages` odspMetadata comparison)\n- Always use the driveId from `list_pages` odspMetadata, NOT from the URL's nav parameter\n- This single character difference (`H` vs `G`) causes 404 \"itemNotFound\" errors\n\n### Platform Notes\n- `python3` unavailable on this Windows machine (Microsoft Store stub) — use `node -e` for all scripting (confirmed from squad notes)\n- `uuidgen` unavailable — use `require('crypto').randomUUID()` in Node.js\n\n## Conventions\n- Loop MCP `list_pages` can return very large results (280K+ chars for workspaces with many pages) — search by itemId programmatically rather than reading raw output\n- The `pageId` field in `list_pages` results can be `undefined` — construct it manually from `odspMetadata` fields: `base64(domain + \",\" + driveId + \",\" + itemId)`\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01E5mZGpyVrtj2zbZ1G3YpAR","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"This was a read-only task — no code changes or PR needed. Here's a reusable skill I discovered:\n\n```skill\n---\nname: read-sharepoint-loop-page\ndescription: Read a Loop page from a SharePoint content storage URL using Loop MCP\nallowed-tools: Bash, mcp__loop__list_pages, mcp__loop__get_page\ntrigger: when given a SharePoint :fl: URL pointing to a Loop page in a content storage container\nscope: squad\nproject: any\n---\n\n# Read Loop Page from SharePoint Content Storage URL\n\n## Steps\n\n1. **Decode the nav parameter** from the URL (it's base64-encoded):\n   ```js\n   const navB64 = '<nav_param_value>';\n   const nav = Buffer.from(navB64, 'base64').toString('utf-8');\n   const params = new URLSearchParams(nav);\n   const driveId = params.get('d'); // URL-decoded driveId\n   const itemId = params.get('f');  // itemId\n   const x = JSON.parse(params.get('x'));\n   const workspaceId = x.w; // base64-encoded ODSP|domain|driveId|itemId\n   ```\n\n2. **List pages** using `mcp__loop__list_pages` with the `workspaceId` from step 1.\n\n3. **Find the target page** by matching `odspMetadata.itemId` in the listing results (use Node.js to parse the large JSON).\n\n4. **Construct pageId** from the LISTING's odspMetadata (NOT the URL's nav params — driveId may differ!):\n   ```js\n   const domain = new URL(odspMetadata.siteUrl).hostname;\n   const pageId = Buffer.from(domain + ',' + odspMetadata.driveId + ',' + odspMetadata.itemId).toString('base64');\n   ```\n\n5. **Read page** via `mcp__loop__get_page` with the constructed `pageId` and `workspaceId`.\n\n## Notes\n- `decode_url` MCP tool does NOT support SharePoint `:fl:` URLs — only `/p/` and `/join/` formats\n- The driveId in URL nav params can differ from the actual driveId (e.g., `MH9F` vs `MG9F`) — always use listing's metadata\n- Use `node -e` for scripting on Windows (python3 unavailable)\n```\n\nNow let me send the Teams notification."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1481,"cache_read_input_tokens":57649,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1481,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4004397f-9402-4049-ba0c-52ed9b7104fc","uuid":"20b5bdd7-19b7-4eb4-8a4b-8b8ac1b7d320"}
